window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>1","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CLASSIFICATION","question":"In the binomial system of naming organisms, the second name is called the","images":[],"options":{"A":"scientific name","B":"common name","C":"generic name","D":"specific name"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In the binomial system of naming organisms, the first name is the genus name and the second name is the species name, also known as the specific name. This system was developed by Carl Linnaeus, and it helps to avoid confusion by providing each species with a unique, scientifically accepted name.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>2","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : FORMS IN WHICH LIVING CELLS EXIST","question":"Which of the following features does not necessarily place paramecium at a higher level of organization over Amoeba?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Presence of cilia","B":"Absence of pseudopodia","C":"Presence of micro and mega nuclei","D":"Presence of more than one food vacuole"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Both Paramecium and Amoeba are single-celled organisms, or protozoans. While Paramecium has cilia and both micro and mega nuclei, Amoeba does not, which places Paramecium at a higher level of organization. However, both Paramecium and Amoeba can have more than one food vacuole. Food vacuoles are structures within the cell that contain food particles engulfed by the cell. Therefore, the presence of more than one food vacuole does not necessarily place Paramecium at a higher level of organization over Amoeba.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>3","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : CELL STRUCTURE AND FUNCTIONS OF CELL COMPONENTS.","question":"The living material of the cell consists of","images":[],"options":{"A":"nucleus and cytoplasm","B":"cytoplasm and vacuole","C":"cytoplasm and cell membrane","D":"nucleus and cell membrane"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The living material of a cell, also known as protoplasm, consists of the nucleus and the cytoplasm. The nucleus is the control center of the cell, containing the cell's DNA, while the cytoplasm is the jelly-like substance that contains the cell's organelles. The cell membrane and vacuole, while important parts of the cell, are not considered part of the living material.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>4","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOSYSTEM","question":"Use the information below to answer this question  A pupil accidentally \"watered\" a potted plant with concentrated salt solution. After sometime the plant began to wilt.    The wilting of the plant is due to the fact that","images":[],"options":{"A":"the root hairs die off and can no longer absorb water","B":"the salt solution causes faster rate of transpiration leading to the death of the plant cells","C":"the salt solution has caused water to be lost from the plant cells leading to loss of turgor","D":"the plant tissue has been poisoned by the salt which is absorbed by the plant"},"answer":"C","explanation":"- The wilting of plant is due to the fact that the salt solution has caused water to be lost from the plant cells leading to loss of turgor.  - Wilting is when a plant becomes limp and flascid.  - Turgor is the pressure produced by a solution in a space that is enclosed by a differentially permeable membrane.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>5","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOSYSTEM","question":"Use the information below to answer this question  A pupil accidentally \"watered\" a potted plant with concentrated salt solution. After sometime the plant began to wilt.  Which of the following activities would revive the plant?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Covering the plant with dark paper to prevent further water loss from its surfaces","B":"Leaving the plant to adapt to the condition","C":"Exposing the plant to high concentration of oxygen","D":"Adding more water to the soil"},"answer":"D","explanation":"- Adding more water to the plant will revive the plant.  - Covering the leaf or placing it in a dark environment will prevent/inhibit photosynthesis.  - Leaving the plant to adapt to the condition might kill the plant  N:B  1. Water is essential in the process of photosynthesis.  2. Carbon dioxide is readily available in the atmosphere, this combines with water to produce organic compounds and oxygen as a by-product in the process of photosynthesis.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>6","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : ORGANIZATION OF LIFE","question":"Primary growth in plants is brought about by the activity of the","images":[],"options":{"A":"meristem","B":"endodermis","C":"epidermis","D":"mesophyll"},"answer":"A","explanation":"- Primary growth in plant is brought by the activities of the meristem.  - Primary growth in a plant is the first growth of the plant and it takes place in the apical meristem.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>7","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Study the diagram and use it to answer this question      To form a ball and socket joint, the structure labelled I fits into another structure in the scapula called the","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"blade","B":"glenoid cavity","C":"olecranon fossa","D":"patella"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The glenoid cavity has a notch which the head of the humerus can fit into.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>8","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Study the diagram and use it to answer this question      The structure labelled II is called","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"deltoid ridge","B":"trochanter","C":"shaft","D":"trochlea"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The structure labelled II is the shaft. The shaft (or diaphysis) is the long, cylindrical, central part of a long bone. In this diagram, it represents the middle section of the bone, distinct from the ends (epiphyses) and other specific features like the deltoid ridge, trochanter, or trochlea.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>9","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"Which of the following parts of the skeleton does not have a protective function?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Ribs","B":"Carpals","C":"Skull","D":"Pelvis"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The protective function of the skeleton is to protect the internal organs of the body. The ribs protect the heart and lungs, the skull protects the brain, and the pelvis protects the reproductive and lower digestive systems. The carpals, however, are the small bones in the wrist and do not have a protective function. They are primarily involved in providing flexibility and movement to the hand.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>10","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"Carbon dioxide is carried in the plasma","images":[],"options":{"A":"in combination with haemoglobin","B":"in combination with antibodies","C":"by capillary action","D":"as bicarbonate ion"},"answer":"D","explanation":"In the blood, most carbon dioxide is present in the form of bicarbonate ions (HCO3-). Carbon dioxide from the body's cells is transported to the lungs or gills for removal from the body. It does this by diffusing into red blood cells within capillaries. Once inside the red blood cells, carbon dioxide combines with water to form carbonic acid (H2CO3), under the influence of an enzyme called carbonic anhydrase. This carbonic acid quickly dissociates to form bicarbonate ions and hydrogen ions. The bicarbonate ions diffuse out of the red blood cells into the plasma of the blood. Hence, carbon dioxide is carried in the plasma as bicarbonate ion.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>11","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : RESPIRATORY SYSTEM","question":"In the adult frog gaseous exchange takes place through the","images":[],"options":{"A":"buccal cavity, skin and lungs","B":"buccal cavity, skin and spiracles","C":"gills, skin and buccal cavity","D":"tympanic membrane, lungs and gills"},"answer":"A","explanation":"In adult frogs, gaseous exchange or respiration takes place through three routes: the buccal cavity, the skin, and the lungs. The buccal cavity and skin are used for respiration when the frog is in water or in a moist environment, while the lungs are used when the frog is on land. The skin of the frog is moist and thin, which makes it permeable to gases. Oxygen can diffuse directly into the blood vessels that are close to the surface of the skin. The buccal cavity also has a moist lining where gas exchange can occur. The lungs are used for respiration when the frog is active or in a dry environment. Spiracles are not present in frogs, they are openings for respiration in insects. Gills are used for respiration in the tadpole stage of the frog, not in the adult stage. The tympanic membrane in frogs is used for hearing, not for respiration.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>12","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REGULATION OF INTERNAL ENVIRONMENT (HOMEOSTASIS)","question":"The process of regulating the amount of water and solutes in the body fluids is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"osmosis","B":"diffusion","C":"osmoregulation","D":"homeostasis"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Osmoregulation is the process of maintaining the balance of water and solutes in the body fluids. It is a type of homeostasis specifically dealing with the regulation of water and electrolyte concentration in the body. Osmosis and diffusion are processes involved in osmoregulation, but they are not the regulation itself. Homeostasis is a broader term that includes all processes that maintain the body's internal environment in a stable, relatively constant state, including but not limited to osmoregulation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>13","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : EXCRETORY SYSTEMS","question":"The presence of glucose in the urine of a patient is an indication of malfunctioning of the","images":[],"options":{"A":"pancreas","B":"gall bladder","C":"liver","D":"spleen"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The presence of glucose in the urine, a condition known as glucosuria, is often a sign of diabetes mellitus. This condition is caused by a malfunctioning pancreas, which is unable to produce enough insulin to regulate blood sugar levels. Insulin is a hormone that helps cells in the body absorb glucose from the bloodstream. When there's not enough insulin, glucose can build up in the blood and eventually be excreted in the urine.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>14","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : HORMONAL COORDINATION","question":"Which of the following statements is not true about hormones?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Hormones are manufactured in ductless glands and poured straight into the blood stream","B":"Hormones are carried by the blood plasma to the required target organs","C":"Hormonal responses are usually swift, instant and electrical","D":"Once the effects of hormones are over, they are inactivated and excreted from the body"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Hormones are chemical messengers that are secreted directly into the blood, which carries them to organs and tissues of the body to exert their functions. They are produced by various glands in the body, including the pituitary, thyroid, and adrenal glands. However, hormonal responses are not usually swift, instant, and electrical. Instead, they are slower and longer-lasting than the responses of the nervous system. This is because hormones must travel through the bloodstream to reach their target cells, which can take some time. Once the effects of hormones are over, they are indeed inactivated and excreted from the body.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>15","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : HORMONAL COORDINATION","question":"Which of the following actions is not a function of adrenalin? It increases","images":[],"options":{"A":"body blood sugar by conversion of liver glycogen into glucose","B":"muscular power and resistance to fatigue","C":"the rate of heart beat","D":"the passage of food"},"answer":"D","explanation":"* The following are the functions of adrenalines  1. It increases heartbeat and respiration  2. It increases the sugar content of the blood  3. It aids dilation of the pupils  4. It increases muscular tone   5. It is responsible for shivering during cold  6. It is associated with fear and anxiety  7. It prepares the body for emergency.    Except for the passage of food","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>16","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : HORMONAL COORDINATION","question":"Plant hormones include the following except","images":[],"options":{"A":"insulin","B":"auxin","C":"cytokinin","D":"gibberellin"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Plant hormones, also known as phytohormones, are chemicals that regulate plant growth. Insulin is not a plant hormone, it is a hormone produced by the pancreas in animals to control blood sugar levels. Auxin, cytokinin, and gibberellin are all examples of plant hormones. Auxin is involved in cell elongation, cytokinin in cell division and gibberellin in stem elongation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>17","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : NERVOUS COORDINATION","question":"The passage of nerve impulse across a synapse is facilitated by the secretion of","images":[],"options":{"A":"acetylcholine","B":"thyroxine","C":"insulin","D":"progesterone"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The passage of nerve impulse across a synapse is facilitated by the secretion of a neurotransmitter called acetylcholine. A synapse is a small gap at the end of a neuron that allows a signal to pass from one neuron to the next. Acetylcholine is released into this gap to transmit the signal to the next neuron. Thyroxine, insulin, and progesterone are hormones, not neurotransmitters.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>18","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : NERVOUS COORDINATION","question":"The part of the brain which controls and coordinates body posture is the","images":[],"options":{"A":"cerebellum","B":"hypothalamus","C":"medulla oblongata","D":"pons varolii"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The cerebellum is a part of the brain that is responsible for motor control. It receives information from the sensory systems, the spinal cord, and other parts of the brain and then regulates motor movements. The cerebellum coordinates voluntary movements such as posture, balance, coordination, and speech, resulting in smooth and balanced muscular activity.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>19","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : NERVOUS COORDINATION","question":"Which of the following processes is not an example of a reflex action?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Blinking of the eye","B":"Reading","C":"Beating of the heart","D":"Sneezing"},"answer":"B","explanation":"- Reading is not a reflex action.  - A reflex action is an involuntary or automatic action in response to impulses initiated stimulus.  - Reflex actions are not consciously controlled.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>20","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"The eyes can properly focus images of objects of various distances on","images":[],"options":{"A":"refraction","B":"reflection","C":"accommodation","D":"correction"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The eyes can properly focus images of objects of various distances on the retina through a process called accommodation. Accommodation is the process by which the vertebrate eye changes optical power to maintain a clear image or focus on an object as its distance varies.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>21","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : SENSE ORGANS","question":"Which of the following sensations may not be detected by the skin?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Touch","B":"Pressure","C":"Stress","D":"Pain"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The skin is an important sense organ. In the dermis of the skin, there are different types of sensory cells or nerve endings, each of which receives one of the following stimuli - pain - heat - cold - touch - pressure.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>22","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"The process by which flowers produce fruit without the process of fertilization is called","images":[],"options":{"A":"viviparity","B":"parthenocarpy","C":"propagation","D":"metamorphosis"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The process by which flowers produce fruit without the process of fertilization is called parthenocarpy. This is a natural or artificially induced process in which fruits are produced without fertilization. The resulting fruits are seedless.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>23","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS","question":"The part of the young root that pushes its way through the soil is the","images":[],"options":{"A":"root hair","B":"tap root","C":"root cap","D":"lateral root"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The part of the young root that pushes its way through the soil is the root cap. The root cap is a type of tissue at the tip of a plant root. It serves to protect the growing tip in plants. It secretes mucilage to ease the movement of the root through soil, and may also be involved in communication with the soil microbiota.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>24","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONCEPT OF LIVING : REPRODUCTION","question":"An example of a dehiscent fruit is","images":[],"options":{"A":"crotalaria","B":"tomato","C":"mango","D":"orange"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Dehiscent fruits are those that split along a built-in line of weakness in a valve where they dehisce (split open) to release their seeds. Crotalaria is an example of a dehiscent fruit. Tomato, mango, and orange are examples of indehiscent fruits, which do not split open to release their seeds when ripe. Hence, the correct answer is option 1.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>25","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : ANIMAL NUTRITION","question":"Which of the following food substances gives the least amount of calories?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Rice","B":"Groundnuts","C":"Cabbage","D":"Egg yolk"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Calories are a measure of energy, and different foods provide different amounts of energy. Among the options provided, cabbage provides the least amount of calories. This is because cabbage is primarily made up of water and fiber, which do not provide a significant amount of energy when consumed.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>26","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"PLANT AND ANIMAL NUTRITION : FEEDING HABITS","question":"Analysis of the gut content of an animal showed that it contained small pieces of bone, seeds, roughage and insects. The animal is likely to be a/an","images":[],"options":{"A":"carnivore","B":"herbivore","C":"insectivore","D":"omnivore"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The content of the gut include:  1. Bone   2. Seeds  3. Roughage  4. Insects  - Bones and insects are mostly found in the guts of carnivores  - Seed and roughage are usually found in the guts of herbivores  - Organisms that exhibit the feeding habit of herbivores and carnivores are called omnivores","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>27","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HIS HEALTH.","question":"Filaments of Spirogyra placed in a beaker of tap water in a dark cupboard died because","images":[],"options":{"A":"the filaments could not photosynthesize","B":"conjugation could not take place","C":"the temperature was too high","D":"the plant was overloaded"},"answer":"A","explanation":"- The filaments of spirogyra placed in a beaker in a dark cupboard dies because the filaments could not photosynthesis.  - The dark environment inhibits photosynthesis in the spirogyra.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>28","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOSYSTEM","question":"The importance of the concentration of chloroplast in the palisade layer of the leaf is for maximum exposure to","images":[],"options":{"A":"carbon dioxide","B":"light","C":"water","D":"oxygen"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Chloroplasts are the site of photosynthesis in plant cells. They contain chlorophyll, the pigment that absorbs light energy. The concentration of chloroplasts in the palisade layer of the leaf is for maximum exposure to light, which is the primary energy source for photosynthesis.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>29","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL COMPONENTS","question":"A community is best defined as","images":[],"options":{"A":"living things in a habitat interacting with the non-living part of the environment.","B":"the total number of individuals of one species of organisms living in a particular habitat","C":"populations of different species living together and interacting with each other in one habitat","D":"the individuals of a particular group living together in an area and sharing the same resources"},"answer":"C","explanation":"A community in ecology is defined as a group of populations of different species living together and interacting with each other in one habitat. It includes all the different species within a certain area, interacting with each other and with their physical environment.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>30","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Which of the following physical factors is likely to affect the distribution of plants in a pond?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Light","B":"Humidity","C":"Wind","D":"Temperature"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Light affects the distribution of plants in a pond because it is necessary for photosynthesis, the process by which plants make food. In a pond, light can be a limiting factor because it decreases with depth. Therefore, plants are usually distributed according to the availability of light, with more light-requiring species near the surface and less light-requiring species in deeper parts.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>31","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : SIMPLE MEASUREMENT OF ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"Which of the following instruments is used to measure wind speed?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Thermometer","B":"Barometer","C":"Hygrometer","D":"Anemometer"},"answer":"D","explanation":"An anemometer is used to measure wind speed. A thermometer measures temperature, a barometer measures atmospheric pressure, and a hygrometer measures humidity.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>32","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : FOOD WEBS AND TROPHIC LEVELS","question":"Study the food web below carefully and use it to answer this question      Tertiary consumers within the web are","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"cat and lion only","B":"man and lion only","C":"man and cat only","D":"man, cat and lion"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Given: The food web in the question; the tertiary consumers are: cat, man and lion.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>33","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : FOOD WEBS AND TROPHIC LEVELS","question":"Study the food web below carefully and use it to answer this question      What would be the effect of taking the lion out of the web?","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"options":{"A":"The number of organisms at each trophic level would increase","B":"Man would occupy the apex of the web","C":"There would be more rabbits in the web","D":"The energy reaching the remaining trophic levels would increase"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Man would occupy the apex of the web if lion is removed.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>34","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ENERGY TRANSFORMATION IN NATURE","question":"Which of the following statements about the transfer of energy in an ecosystem is correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Energy increases at higher trophic levels","B":"More organisms can be supported at higher levels","C":"There are fewer organisms at lower trophic levels","D":"Energy is lost at each trophic level"},"answer":"D","explanation":"- Energy is lost at each trophic level in an ecosystem.  - The producers is fed on by the primary consumer, the amount of energy in the producer reduces to a level, when the primary consumer is fed on by the secondary consumer, the amount of energy in the primary consumer reduces to another level.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>35","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"Pond weeds normally lack thick layers of cuticle because","images":[],"options":{"A":"their system of photosynthesis is not efficient","B":"there is no danger of becoming desiccated","C":"their leaves are either dissected or ribbon-shaped","D":"there are numerous stomata on their upper epidermis"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Pond weeds lack a thick cuticle layer because they live in an aquatic environment where there is no danger of water loss or desiccation. The cuticle layer in plants is a waxy, water-repelling layer that prevents water loss from the plant's surface. In an aquatic environment, this is not necessary as there is an abundance of water.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>36","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOSYSTEM","question":"Shrubs do not survive on newly weathered soils because","images":[],"options":{"A":"the top soil is shallow","B":"drainage on such soil is poor","C":"humus is absent from the soil","D":"the soil tends to be sandy"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Newly weathered soils often have a shallow layer of topsoil, which can restrict the growth of shrubs and other plants due to limited nutrient availability and poor root development.  But typically, newly weathered soils lack mature humus or organic matter, which is crucial for nutrient availability and soil structure. This can indeed affect plant growth, but in the context of shrubs not surviving, the shallow topsoil is usually the more critical factor because it limits root penetration and nutrient access.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>37","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : ECOLOGICAL FACTORS","question":"The speed of the flow of water in a river is faster in the middle than along the banks due to","images":[],"options":{"A":"differences in turbidity at different parts of the river","B":"the abundance of fishes and other organisms along the bank","C":"reduced force of gravity in the middle portion of the river","D":"resistance offered by the walls of the banks"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The speed of the flow of water in a river is faster in the middle than along the banks due to the resistance offered by the walls of the banks. This is because the friction between the water and the river bank slows down the water flow near the banks. This concept is known as 'boundary layer' in fluid dynamics, where the velocity of fluid (in this case, water) is zero at the boundary (river bank) and increases as we move towards the center.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>38","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : WAYS OF ENSURING CONSERVATION","question":"The effects of environmental degradation caused by human activities can be controlled by the following measures except","images":[],"options":{"A":"reclaiming the land","B":"converting mining pits into fish ponds","C":"resettling indigenous inhabitants","D":"educating people"},"answer":"B","explanation":"- Converting mining pits into fish ponds promotes environmental degradation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>39","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGY OF POPULATION : ECOLOGICAL SUCCESSION","question":"The following observations concerning succession are true except that the","images":[],"options":{"A":"pioneer community has fewer species","B":"middle stages communities are most diverse","C":"climax community has the greatest number of species","D":"total biomass of the community increase as succession progresses"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The climax community, also known as the maximum or stable community, does not have the greatest number of species. Instead, it is characterized by a stable equilibrium with a relatively constant number of species and populations, which may not necessarily be the highest in terms of species diversity compared to earlier stages of succession. The highest diversity often occurs in the intermediate stages of succession.    Note: In ecological succession, the climax community does not typically have the greatest number of species; rather, it is characterized by stability and equilibrium, while the highest species diversity is often found in the intermediate stages.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>40","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : TOWARDS BETTER HEALTH","question":"A vaccine is introduced into a person's body to","images":[],"options":{"A":"destroy all disease-causing organisms in the body","B":"stimulate the body to produce antibodies","C":"enhance the production of red blood cells","D":"isolate disease-causing pathogens from the blood"},"answer":"B","explanation":"A vaccine is a biological preparation that provides active acquired immunity to a particular infectious disease. A vaccine typically contains an agent that resembles a disease-causing microorganism and is often made from weakened or killed forms of the microbe, its toxins, or one of its surface proteins. The agent stimulates the body's immune system to recognize the agent as a threat, destroy it, and to further recognize and destroy any of the microorganisms associated with that agent that it may encounter in the future. Hence, the correct answer is 'stimulate the body to produce antibodies'.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>41","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"ECOLOGICAL MANAGEMENT : ADAPTATION OF ORGANISMS TO HABITATS.","question":"Which of the following activities constitutes biological control?","images":[],"options":{"A":"A small bony fish transported on the back of a shark","B":"Adding manure to crops in a garden","C":"Tilapia feeding on the larvae and pupae of mosquito","D":"A vulture feeding on the carcass of a goat"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Biological control is a method of controlling pests such as insects, mites, weeds and plant diseases using other organisms. It relies on predation, parasitism, herbivory, or other natural mechanisms, but typically also involves an active human management role. In this case, 'Tilapia feeding on the larvae and pupae of mosquito' is an example of biological control because the Tilapia (a type of fish) is being used to control the population of mosquitoes by feeding on their larvae and pupae.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>42","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"MICROORGANISMS: MAN AND HEALTH : TOWARDS BETTER HEALTH","question":"Many diseases caused by bacteria can be treated and cured by using","images":[],"options":{"A":"antiseptics","B":"antibiotics","C":"antigens","D":"antibodies"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Bacterial diseases can be treated and cured using antibiotics. Antibiotics are drugs that either kill bacteria or prevent them from multiplying, thus helping the body's immune system to fight the bacterial infection.","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>43","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : WAYS OF ENSURING CONSERVATION","question":"To avoid over-fishing in a lake, the following measures may be helpful except","images":[],"options":{"A":"limiting fishing periods","B":"regulating the size of nets","C":"fishing throughout the year","D":"fish breeding exercise"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Fishing throughout the year can lead to over-fishing as it does not allow time for the fish population to replenish. The other options like limiting fishing periods, regulating the size of nets, and fish breeding exercises are measures that can help avoid over-fishing.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>44","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"CONSERVATION OF NATURAL RESOURCES : WAYS OF ENSURING CONSERVATION","question":"Conservation may be promoted by","images":[],"options":{"A":"encouraging tree planting","B":"systematic deforestation","C":"overgrazing of pastures","D":"unabated bush burning"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Conservation is the practice of caring for natural resources so they can sustainably support life. One of the ways to promote conservation is by encouraging tree planting. Trees help to conserve soil and water, provide habitat for wildlife, and absorb carbon dioxide from the atmosphere. Therefore, encouraging tree planting promotes conservation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>45","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BASIC ECOLOGICAL CONCEPTS : NUTRIENT CYCLING IN NATURE","question":"Which of the following substances is not recycled in an ecosystem?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Carbon","B":"Energy","C":"Water","D":"Nitrogen"},"answer":"B","explanation":"In an ecosystem, substances like carbon, water, and nitrogen are recycled through various biogeochemical cycles. However, energy is not recycled in an ecosystem. Instead, it flows through the ecosystem in one direction, from producers to consumers and decomposers. This is known as the 'one-way flow of energy'. The energy that enters the ecosystem as sunlight is used by producers (like plants) in photosynthesis to make food. Consumers (like animals) eat the producers and get energy. Finally, decomposers break down dead plants and animals, releasing the energy back into the environment as heat. Therefore, energy is not recycled in an ecosystem.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>46","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"Which of the following statements about phenylthiocarbamide (PTC) is not correct?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Some people find the taste of PTC to be bitter","B":"Others find this substance to be tasteless","C":"Ability to taste this chemical is heritable","D":"Ability to taste the chemical is not heritable"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The ability to taste phenylthiocarbamide (PTC) is indeed heritable. This is a well-known example of a simple genetic trait in humans. People who find PTC to taste bitter have a dominant gene for tasting PTC, while those who find it tasteless have a recessive gene. Therefore, the statement 'Ability to taste the chemical is not heritable' is not correct.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>47","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"Which of the following characters is not an example of discontinuous variation?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Skin colour","B":"Fingerprint","C":"Ability to roll tongue","D":"Sex type"},"answer":"A","explanation":"Discontinuous variation refers to the variation in characteristics that have a limited number of appearances, such as blood type or eye color. These characteristics are typically controlled by a single gene pair. Skin color, on the other hand, is an example of continuous variation, where characteristics fall into a range and are controlled by multiple gene pairs. Therefore, skin color is not an example of discontinuous variation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>48","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"VARIATION IN POPULATION : MORPHOLOGICAL VARIATIONS","question":"Which of the following human traits in a class of school children may give an approximate normal distribution curve when the variation is plotted?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Blood groups","B":"Ear shapes","C":"Sex distribution","D":"Heights"},"answer":"D","explanation":"A normal distribution curve is a statistical analysis that results in a bell-shaped curve. It is used to represent data that clusters around a mean or average. Height in a class of school children is likely to give an approximate normal distribution curve when the variation is plotted because height varies among individuals and tends to cluster around an average value. Other options like blood groups, ear shapes, and sex distribution are not likely to give a normal distribution as they are discrete variables.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>49","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"The observable characteristic of an individual usually resulting from the interaction between the gene composition and the environment is referred to as","images":[],"options":{"A":"allele","B":"genotype","C":"phenotype","D":"chromosome"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The observable characteristic of an individual, usually resulting from the interaction between the gene composition and the environment, is referred to as the phenotype. The phenotype is the physical expression, or characteristics, of that individual. It is influenced by both the individual's genotype, which is the set of genes an individual carries, and by the environment.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>50","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"The sudden change in a gene structure or chromosome number in an organism likely to cause an inheritable change in the phenotype is known as","images":[],"options":{"A":"migration","B":"mutation","C":"mitosis","D":"meiosis"},"answer":"B","explanation":"This is the definition of 'mutation'   - Mutation is the sudden change in a gene structure or chromosome number in an organism and its likely to cause an inheritable change in the phenotype.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>51","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : TRANSMISSION AND EXPRESSION OF CHARACTERISTICS IN ORGANISMS","question":"The defective cells involved in sickle-cell anaemia disease are","images":[],"options":{"A":"phagocytes","B":"lymphocytes","C":"erythrocytes","D":"thrombocytes"},"answer":"C","explanation":"Sickle-cell anaemia is a genetic disease that affects the erythrocytes, or red blood cells. In this disease, the red blood cells become rigid and sticky, and are shaped like sickles or crescent moons. These irregularly shaped cells can get stuck in small blood vessels, which can slow or block blood flow and oxygen to parts of the body.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>52","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : GENETIC TERMINOLOGIES","question":"What does the chemical composition of the genetic material of all living organisms consist of?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Deoxyribonucleic acid","B":"Adenosine diphosphate","C":"Adenosine triphosphate","D":"Follicle stimulating hormone"},"answer":"A","explanation":"The genetic material of all living organisms consists of Deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA). DNA is a molecule composed of two chains that coil around each other to form a double helix carrying genetic instructions for the development, functioning, growth and reproduction of all known organisms and many viruses. DNA and RNA are nucleic acids; alongside proteins, lipids and complex carbohydrates (polysaccharides), nucleic acids are one of the four major types of macromolecules that are essential for all known forms of life.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>53","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : CHROMOSOMES","question":"Which of the following occurrences  is not a feature of meiosis","images":[],"options":{"A":"Formation of four haploid cells","B":"Two successive nuclear cell divisions","C":"Pairing of homologous chromosomes at prophase","D":"Formation of two diploid cells"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Meiosis is a type of cell division that reduces the number of chromosomes in the parent cell by half and produces four gamete cells. This process is required to produce egg and sperm cells for sexual reproduction. During meiosis, diploid cells undergo two cell divisions to produce haploid cells. Therefore, the formation of two diploid cells is not a feature of meiosis.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>54","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : LINKAGE, SEX DETERMINATION AND SEX LINKED CHARACTERS","question":"Which of the following diseases is commonly observed in human males and is sex-linked?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Beriberi","B":"Down's syndrome","C":"Sickle-cell anaemia","D":"Colour blindness"},"answer":"D","explanation":"Colour blindness is a sex-linked disease. Sex-linked diseases are diseases that are determined by genes found on sex chromosomes. In humans, the genes for color blindness are located on the X chromosome. Since males have only one X chromosome, they are more likely to have color blindness than females, who have two X chromosomes.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>55","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"BIOLOGY OF HEREDITY (GENETICS) : PROBABILITY IN GENETICS (HYBRID FORMATION)","question":"If red is dominant to white and homozygous red pea-plants are crossed with homozygous white pea-plants, the first filial generation will have","images":[],"options":{"A":"2 red flowers, 2 white flowers","B":"4 red flowers","C":"4 white flowers","D":"4 pink flowers"},"answer":"B","explanation":"- Let the white pea plants be rr  - Let the red pea plants be RR  Given: Red is dominant to while      Since red is dominant to white, the offspring in the first filial generation are all red.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>56","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"The resemblance of a palatable insect to a poisonous insect is an example of","images":[],"options":{"A":"a chemical deterrent to a predator","B":"an escape from the predator by camouflage","C":"an escape from the predator by mimicry","D":"a defence against the predator by warning colouration"},"answer":"C","explanation":"The resemblance of a palatable insect to a poisonous insect is an example of mimicry. Mimicry is a survival strategy where an organism, in this case a palatable insect, resembles another organism, a poisonous insect, in order to deceive predators into thinking it is harmful. This helps the palatable insect to avoid being eaten by predators.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>57","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : BEHAVIOURAL ADAPTATIONS IN SOCIAL ANIMALS.","question":"Which of the following statements is not true of the worker termites? They","images":[],"options":{"A":"build and repair the nest","B":"produce enzymes to digest cellulose","C":"search for food to feed the colony","D":"look after the nymph"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The worker termites do not help to digest cellulose, the only cultivate fungus garden, this is to digest the wood on which it grows to a state the termite can use.","marks":"1","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>58","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"Which of the following occurrences cannot be taken as a direct observation of Natural Selection in recent times?","images":[],"options":{"A":"Industrial melanism in moths","B":"Selective breeding in cattle","C":"Insecticide resistance of some mosquitoes","D":"Development of long necks in giraffes"},"answer":"B","explanation":"Selective breeding in cattle is not a direct observation of Natural Selection. Natural Selection is a process where organisms that are better adapted to their environment tend to survive and produce more offspring. This process is natural and not influenced by human intervention. On the other hand, selective breeding is a process where humans intentionally breed animals with desirable traits to produce offspring with those traits. This is a form of artificial selection, not natural selection.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>59","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"The accepted concepts for the theory of Natural Selection does not include","images":[],"options":{"A":"tendency for organisms to overproduce","B":"struggle for existence","C":"survival of the fittest","D":"use and disuse of body parts"},"answer":"D","explanation":"The concept of 'use and disuse of body parts' is not included in the theory of Natural Selection. This concept is actually part of Lamarck's theory of evolution, which suggests that an organism can change during its lifetime in response to its environment, and those changes are then passed onto its offspring. However, this theory has been largely discredited in favor of Darwin's theory of Natural Selection, which states that genetic changes occur randomly, and those that benefit the organism are more likely to be passed on to the next generation.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"objective>Biology>2008>60","subject":"Biology","year":"2008","type":"Objective","topic":"ADAPTATION FOR SURVIVAL AND EVOLUTION : EVOLUTION","question":"The order of evolutionary trend in plants is","images":[],"options":{"A":"Bryophyta, Thallophyta,  Pteridophyta and Spermatophyta","B":"Thallophyta, Bryophyta, Pteridophyta and Spermatophyta","C":"Spermatophyta, Pteridophyta, Bryophyta and Thallophyta","D":"Bryophyta, Pteridophyta, Spermatophyta and Thallophyta"},"answer":"B","explanation":"The correct order of evolutionary trend in plants is Thallophyta, Bryophyta, Pteridophyta and Spermatophyta. Thallophyta are the most primitive plants, followed by Bryophyta (mosses and liverworts), Pteridophyta (ferns and their relatives), and finally Spermatophyta (seed plants), which are the most advanced.","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"}];